<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900629-0025</DOCNO><DOCID>900629-0025.</DOCID><HL>   Toyota Plans to buy   U.S.-Supplied Chips   Over Next 3 Years</HL><DATE>06/29/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A2</SO><CO>   TOYOY MOT INTC NSM IRF TXN</CO><IN>AUTOMOBILES (AUT)SEMICONDUCTORS, INTEGRATED CHIPS (SEM)DOW JONES INTERVIEW (CEO)</IN><LP>   WASHINGTON -- The Toyota group announced plans to purchaseas much as $94 million in U.S.-supplied semiconductors foruse in its world-wide car production over the next threeyears.   Hironobu Ono, a Toyota Motor Corp. electronics engineeringmanager, announced these purchasing plans after assuring U.S.trade officials that Toyota and its family of suppliers aredoing their part in increasing U.S. access to the Japanesesemiconductor market. Mr. Ono said that U.S. suppliers likelywill increase their share of the group's semiconductorbusiness to 10.9% in 1992 from 2.1% in 1989.</LP><TEXT>   Toyota announced that, in addition to its purchases ofU.S. standard chips, it has chosen five U.S. semiconductormakers to deliver as many as 23 types of custom-made devicesfor controlling transmission, suspension, engine, audio andother automotive functions. The U.S. vendors are MotorolaInc., Intel Corp., National Semiconductor Corp.,International Rectifier Corp. and Texas Instruments Inc.   Mr. Ono said these U.S. devices could cost a little morethan the Japanese ones that they are intended to replace, butare comparable in quality.   A Motorola spokesman said plans by Toyota and otherJapanese carmakers to expand their purchases of U.S.semiconductors could push the U.S. closer to its goal ofcapturing 20% of the Japanese semiconductor market. The U.S.share currently is 11%.</TEXT></DOC>